{"id":"2205.03288","submitter":"Matthew Webb","authors":"James G. MacKinnon, Morten {\\O}rregaard Nielsen, Matthew D. Webb","title":"Leverage, Influence, and the Jackknife in Clustered Regression Models:\n  Reliable Inference Using summclust","comments":"The summclust package is available here:\n  https://github.com/mattdwebb/summclust","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"econ.EM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Cluster-robust inference is widely used in modern empirical work in economics\nand many other disciplines. When data are clustered, the key unit of\nobservation is the cluster. We propose measures of \"high-leverage\" clusters and\n\"influential\" clusters for linear regression models. The measures of leverage\nand partial leverage, and functions of them, can be used as diagnostic tools to\nidentify datasets and regression designs in which cluster-robust inference is\nlikely to be challenging. The measures of influence can provide valuable\ninformation about how the results depend on the data in the various clusters.\nWe also show how to calculate two jackknife variance matrix estimators, CV3 and\nCV3J, as a byproduct of our other computations. All these quantities, including\nthe jackknife variance estimators, are computed in a new Stata package called\nsummclust that summarizes the cluster structure of a dataset.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 6 May 2022 15:14:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-09"}
